{"title_page": "National Cabinet of Australia", "text_new": "{{use Australian English|date=March 2020}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{confuse|National Security Committee (Australia)|National COVID-19 Coordination Commission}}\n{{Politics of Australia sidebar}}\nThe '''National Cabinet''' is a special intergovernmental decision-making forum composed of the head of the [[Australian government|Commonwealth]] (the [[Prime Minister of Australia|Prime Minister]]) and the [[premiers and chief ministers of the Australian states and territories]], established on 18 March 2020 to coordinate the national response to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Australia]].\n\n==History and description==\nThe formation of the National Cabinet was announced by Prime Minister [[Scott Morrison]] on Wednesday 18 March 2020 following a meeting of the [[Council of Australian Governments]]<ref name=martin>{{cite web | last=Martin | first=Sarah | title=PM tells Australians to 'stop hoarding' as he announces sweeping measures to slow spread of coronavirus | website=the Guardian | date=18 March 2020 | url=http://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/mar/18/pm-tells-australians-to-stop-hoarding-as-he-announces-sweeping-measures-to-slow-spread-of-coronavirus | access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> on 13 March 2020. It was created via the \"National Partnership on Covid-19 Response\" agreement<ref name=natpart>[https://www.coag.gov.au/sites/default/files/communique/covid19-npa.pdf National Partnership on Covid-19 Response]</ref> to \"coordinate and deliver a consistent national response to [[COVID-19]]\" during the global [[2019-2020 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=shoebridge>{{cite web | last=Shoebridge | first=Michael | title=The national cabinet is key to our coronavirus response. Here's how it will need to work | website=The Canberra Times | date=18 March 2020 | url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6684142/the-national-cabinet-is-key-to-our-coronavirus-response-heres-how-it-will-need-to-work/ | access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite document|url=https://www.pm.gov.au/media/transcript-press-conference|title= Press Conference Transcript|publisher= [[Prime Minister's Office]] |date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=afr18mar>{{cite web | last=Burton | first=Tom | title=National cabinet creates a new federal model | website=Australian Financial Review | date=18 March 2020 | url=https://www.afr.com/politics/federal/national-cabinet-creates-a-new-federal-model-20200318-p54bar | access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nIt has been described as akin to [[War cabinet#Australia|Australia's War Cabinet]] during the Second World War.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.thesaturdaypaper.com.au/news/politics/2020/03/21/inside-morrisons-covid-19-war-cabinet/15847092009562|title= Inside Morrison\u2019s Covid-19 war cabinet|work= The Saturday Paper|first=Karen|last=Middleton|author-link=Karen Middleton| issue= 293 |date= 21\u201327 March 2020|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nMeetings of the Cabinet are held using secure [[video conferencing ]].<ref name=afr18mar/>\n\n==Role and responsibilities==\nThe National Cabinet is responsible for endorsing and coordinating national actions in Australia in response to the coronavirus pandemic. It is advised and supported by the [[Australian Health Protection Principal Committee]] (AHPPC),<ref name=ahppc>{{cite web | title=Australian Health Protection Principal Committee (AHPPC) | website=Australian Government Department of Health | date=6 February 2020 | url=https://www.health.gov.au/committees-and-groups/australian-health-protection-principal-committee-ahppc | access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> an ongoing body composed of the [[Chief Medical Officer]] of the [[Commonwealth of Australia|Commonwealth]], [[Brendan Murphy (Australian doctor)|Brendan Murphy]], and the Chief Health Officers of the [[Australian states and territories|states and territories]].<ref name=\"Prime Minister of Australia\">{{cite web | title=Coronavirus measures endorsed by National Cabinet |series=Media release | website=Prime Minister of Australia |publisher=[[Prime Minister's Office (Australia)|Prime Minister's Office]]| url=https://www.pm.gov.au/media/coronavirus-measures-endorsed-national-cabinet | access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> The APPHC  uses the currently available [[data modelling|modelling]], research and data to inform the decisions made by the National Cabinet.<ref name=menziesconv>{{cite web | last=Menzies | first=Jennifer | title=Explainer: what is the national cabinet and is it democratic? | website=The Conversation | date=31 March 2020 | url=http://theconversation.com/explainer-what-is-the-national-cabinet-and-is-it-democratic-135036 | access-date=31 March 2020|quote=CC BY-ND 4.0}}</ref>\n\nThe Prime Minister said that the National Cabinet has \"the status of a cabinet meeting\" at a federal level, meaning it has the same confidentiality and [[Freedom of Information]] protections as the [[Cabinet of Australia|federal cabinet]], under the ''[[Freedom of Information Act 1982]]''.<ref name=afr18mar/> The [[legal authority]] for much of this structure is based on practice and convention, contained in the official ''Cabinet Handbook'';<ref>{{cite book|url=https://www.pmc.gov.au/sites/default/files/publications/cabinet-handbook-13th-edition_0.pdf|edition=13th|title=Cabinet Handbook|author=Commonwealth of Australia. Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet, |isbn=978-1-925364-00-2|date=2019|access-date=30 March 2020|quote=[[CC BY 4.0]]}}</ref> strictly speaking, based on the [[Westminster system]], cabinet decisions do not of themselves have legal authority. This comes from the [[Federal Executive Council (Australia)|Federal Executive Council]], which gives legal force to decisions made by the cabinet.  \"Members of the Cabinet must publicly support all Government decisions made in the Cabinet, even if they do not agree with them. Cabinet ministers cannot dissociate themselves from, or repudiate the decisions of their Cabinet colleagues unless they resign from the Cabinet\".<ref name=afr18mar/> The \"National Partnership on Covid-19 Response\" states in Part 6 (46) that the parties \"do not intend any of the provisions of this Agreement to be legally enforceable\".<ref name =natpart/>\n\nPublic policy specialist Jennifer Menzies describes the National Cabinet as \"COAG by another name\", which has taken on a leadership role during a time of national crisis. She writes \"Though called a cabinet, the national cabinet is technically an intergovernmental forum. The conventions and rules of cabinet, such as cabinet solidarity and the secrecy provisions, do not apply to the national cabinet. Its power is that which the leaders of all Australian jurisdictions bring to negotiate on behalf of their people, and to implement the decisions reached. This model is called [[executive federalism]]. In this model, the citizens of each state or territory are represented by their elected heads, and the smaller states have equal representation. A forum such as the national cabinet is open to criticism as undemocratic, as the role of the [[Australian Parliament]] is put to one side. However, the National Cabinet is based on negotiation and compromise among the states, rather than the will of the majority. Parliament is suspended rather than [[prorogue]]d (dissolved); Parliament will pass legislation based on decisions made by the National Cabinet. Once the crisis has passed, all decisions taken by the Cabinet will fall under the scrutiny of normal democratic processes and thus be accountable for all decisions taken.<ref name=menziesconv/>\n\n==Current membership==\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n!Name!!Office held!!In office since!!colspan=\"2\"|Party\n|-\n|[[Scott Morrison]] [[Australian House of Representatives|MP]]\n|[[Prime Minister of Australia|Prime Minister]] of Australia\n|{{dts|2018|08|24|format=dmy}}\n| {{Australian party style|Liberal}}|&nbsp;\n|[[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]]\n|-\n|[[Gladys Berejiklian]] [[New South Wales Legislative Assembly|MP]]\n|[[Premier of New South Wales|Premier]] of [[New South Wales]]\n|{{dts|2017|01|23|format=dmy}}\n| {{Australian party style|Liberal}}|&nbsp;\n|[[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]]\n|-\n|[[Daniel Andrews]] [[Victorian Legislative Assembly|MP]]\n|[[Premier of Victoria|Premier]] of [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]\n|{{dts|2014|12|4|format=dmy}}\n| {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp;\n|[[Australian Labor Party|Labor]]\n|-\n|[[Annastacia Palaszczuk]] [[Legislative Assembly of Queensland|MP]]\n|[[Premier of Queensland|Premier]] of [[Queensland]]\n|{{dts|2015|2|14|format=dmy}}\n| {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp;\n|[[Australian Labor Party|Labor]]\n|-\n|[[Mark McGowan]] [[Western Australian Legislative Assembly|MLA]]\n|[[Premier of Western Australia|Premier]] of [[Western Australia]] \n|{{dts|2017|03|17|format=dmy}}\n| {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp;\n|[[Australian Labor Party|Labor]]\n|-\n|[[Steven Marshall]] [[South Australian House of Assembly|MP]]\n|[[Premier of South Australia|Premier]] of [[South Australia]]\n|{{dts|2018|3|19|format=dmy}}\n| {{Australian party style|Liberal}}|&nbsp;\n|[[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]]\n|-\n|[[Peter Gutwein]] [[Tasmanian House of Assembly|MHA]]\n|[[Premier of Tasmania|Premier]] of [[Tasmania]]\n|{{dts|2020|01|20|format=dmy}}\n| {{Australian party style|Liberal}}|&nbsp;\n|[[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]]\n|-\n|[[Andrew Barr]] [[Australian Capital Territory Legislative Assembly|MLA]]\n|[[Chief Minister of the Australian Capital Territory|Chief Minister]] of the [[Australian Capital Territory]]\n|{{dts|2014|12|11|format=dmy}}\n| {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp;\n|[[Australian Labor Party|Labor]]\n|-\n|[[Michael Gunner]] [[Northern Territory Legislative Assembly|MLA]]\n|[[Chief Minister of the Northern Territory|Chief Minister]] of the [[Northern Territory]]\n|{{dts|2016|8|31|format=dmy}}\n| {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp;\n|[[Australian Labor Party|Labor]]\n|}\n\n==Meetings and press releases==\n*16 March 2020: Announcement of a \"significant step-up\" to the pandemic, upon the advice of the AHPPC, with additional measures in order to reduce community transmission. These included banning [[cruise ship]]s from docking, enhanced screening of arrivals, and mandatory [[self-isolation]] for everyone arriving in Australia. The Cabinet also activated the second stage of the ''Australian Health Sector Emergency Response Plan for Novel Coronavirus'', which \"enables governments to undertake targeted action... and ensures that resources are properly allocated where needed and the risks to vulnerable people in the community are mitigated\".<ref>{{cite web | title=Coronavirus measures endorsed by National Cabinet | website=Prime Minister of Australia | url=https://www.pm.gov.au/media/coronavirus-measures-endorsed-national-cabinet | access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n*25 March 2020: PM announces creation of the [[National COVID-19 Coordination Commission]] (NCCC), and clarifies role of various bodies: the National Cabinet \"continues to lead the national response at a government level. The [[National Security Committee of Cabinet]]\u2019s COVID-19 Taskforce and the Expenditure Review Committee of Cabinet continue to take decisions that determine the Commonwealth\u2019s response to the global COVID-19 pandemic\".<ref>{{cite web | title=National Covid-19 Coordination Commission | website=Prime Minister of Australia | url=https://www.pm.gov.au/media/national-covid-19-coordination-commission | access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n*29 March 2020: The Cabinet noted that the rate of increase of the spread of COVID-19 was slowing, but overall numbers were still increasing and welcomed the new coronavirus [[app]] and [[WhatsApp]] channel released by the Government. It announced new limits to indoor and outdoor gatherings to two persons only (with some exceptions); discussed further [[social distancing]] measures; gave further advice to [[senior citizens]]; and agreed to a [[moratorium]] on [[eviction]]s for the coming six months for both commercial and residential [[tenancies]] suffering financial distress.<ref name=mr20mar>{{cite web | title=National Cabinet Statement | website=Prime Minister of Australia | url=https://www.pm.gov.au/media/national-cabinet-statement  | access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Cabinet of Australia]]\n* [[Council of Australian Governments]]\n* [[Loan Council]]\n* [[National Security Committee (Australia)|National Security Committee]]\n* [[War cabinet#Australia|War Cabinet of Australia]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n\n{{Politics of Australia}}\n\n[[Category:Government of Australia]]\n[[Category:Council of Australian Governments]]\n[[Category:2020 in Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{use Australian English|date=March 2020}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{confuse|National Security Committee (Australia)|National COVID-19 Coordination Commission}}\n{{Politics of Australia sidebar}}\nThe '''National Cabinet''' is a special intergovernmental decision-making forum composed of the head of the [[Australian government|Commonwealth]] (the [[Prime Minister of Australia|Prime Minister]]) and the [[premiers and chief ministers of the Australian states and territories]], established on 18 March 2020 to coordinate the national response to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Australia]].\n\n==History and description==\nThe formation of the National Cabinet was announced by Prime Minister [[Scott Morrison]] on Wednesday 18 March 2020 following a meeting of the [[Council of Australian Governments]]<ref name=martin>{{cite web | last=Martin | first=Sarah | title=PM tells Australians to 'stop hoarding' as he announces sweeping measures to slow spread of coronavirus | website=the Guardian | date=18 March 2020 | url=http://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/mar/18/pm-tells-australians-to-stop-hoarding-as-he-announces-sweeping-measures-to-slow-spread-of-coronavirus | access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> on 13 March 2020. It was created via the \"National Partnership on Covid-19 Response\" agreement<ref name=natpart>[https://www.coag.gov.au/sites/default/files/communique/covid19-npa.pdf National Partnership on Covid-19 Response]</ref> to \"coordinate and deliver a consistent national response to [[COVID-19]]\" during the global [[2019-2020 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=shoebridge>{{cite web | last=Shoebridge | first=Michael | title=The national cabinet is key to our coronavirus response. Here's how it will need to work | website=The Canberra Times | date=18 March 2020 | url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6684142/the-national-cabinet-is-key-to-our-coronavirus-response-heres-how-it-will-need-to-work/ | access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite document|url=https://www.pm.gov.au/media/transcript-press-conference|title= Press Conference Transcript|publisher= [[Prime Minister's Office]] |date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=afr18mar>{{cite web | last=Burton | first=Tom | title=National cabinet creates a new federal model | website=Australian Financial Review | date=18 March 2020 | url=https://www.afr.com/politics/federal/national-cabinet-creates-a-new-federal-model-20200318-p54bar | access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nIt has been described as akin to [[War cabinet#Australia|Australia's War Cabinet]] during the Second World War.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.thesaturdaypaper.com.au/news/politics/2020/03/21/inside-morrisons-covid-19-war-cabinet/15847092009562|title= Inside Morrison\u2019s Covid-19 war cabinet|work= The Saturday Paper|first=Karen|last=Middleton|author-link=Karen Middleton| issue= 293 |date= 21\u201327 March 2020|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nMeetings of the Cabinet are held using secure [[video conferencing ]].<ref name=afr18mar/>\n\n==Role and responsibilities==\nThe National Cabinet is responsible for endorsing and coordinating national actions in Australia in response to the coronavirus pandemic. It is advised and supported by the [[Australian Health Protection Principal Committee]] (AHPPC),<ref name=ahppc>{{cite web | title=Australian Health Protection Principal Committee (AHPPC) | website=Australian Government Department of Health | date=6 February 2020 | url=https://www.health.gov.au/committees-and-groups/australian-health-protection-principal-committee-ahppc | access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> an ongoing body composed of the [[Chief Medical Officer]] of the [[Commonwealth of Australia|Commonwealth]], [[Brendan Murphy (Australian doctor)|Brendan Murphy]], and the Chief Health Officers of the [[Australian states and territories|states and territories]].<ref name=\"Prime Minister of Australia\">{{cite web | title=Coronavirus measures endorsed by National Cabinet |series=Media release | website=Prime Minister of Australia |publisher=[[Prime Minister's Office (Australia)|Prime Minister's Office]]| url=https://www.pm.gov.au/media/coronavirus-measures-endorsed-national-cabinet | access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> The APPHC  uses the currently available [[data modelling|modelling]], research and data to inform the decisions made by the National Cabinet.<ref name=menziesconv>{{cite web | last=Menzies | first=Jennifer | title=Explainer: what is the national cabinet and is it democratic? | website=The Conversation | date=31 March 2020 | url=http://theconversation.com/explainer-what-is-the-national-cabinet-and-is-it-democratic-135036 | access-date=31 March 2020|quote=CC BY-ND 4.0}}</ref>\n\nThe Prime Minister said that the National Cabinet has \"the status of a cabinet meeting\" at a federal level, meaning it has the same confidentiality and [[Freedom of Information]] protections as the [[Cabinet of Australia|federal cabinet]], under the ''[[Freedom of Information Act 1982]]''.<ref name=afr18mar/> The [[legal authority]] for much of this structure is based on practice and convention, contained in the official ''Cabinet Handbook'';<ref>{{cite book|url=https://www.pmc.gov.au/sites/default/files/publications/cabinet-handbook-13th-edition_0.pdf|edition=13th|title=Cabinet Handbook|author=Commonwealth of Australia. Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet, |isbn=978-1-925364-00-2|date=2019|access-date=30 March 2020|quote=[[CC BY 4.0]]}}</ref> strictly speaking, based on the [[Westminster system]], cabinet decisions do not of themselves have legal authority. This comes from the [[Federal Executive Council (Australia)|Federal Executive Council]], which gives legal force to decisions made by the cabinet.  \"Members of the Cabinet must publicly support all Government decisions made in the Cabinet, even if they do not agree with them. Cabinet ministers cannot dissociate themselves from, or repudiate the decisions of their Cabinet colleagues unless they resign from the Cabinet\".<ref name=afr18mar/> The \"National Partnership on Covid-19 Response\" states in Part 6 (46) that the parties \"do not intend any of the provisions of this Agreement to be legally enforceable\".<ref name =natpart/>\n\nPublic policy specialist Jennifer Menzies describes the National Cabinet as \"COAG by another name\", which has taken on a leadership role during a time of national crisis. She writes \"Though called a cabinet, the national cabinet is technically an intergovernmental forum. The conventions and rules of cabinet, such as cabinet solidarity and the secrecy provisions, do not apply to the national cabinet. Its power is that which the leaders of all Australian jurisdictions bring to negotiate on behalf of their people, and to implement the decisions reached. This model is called [[executive federalism]]. In this model, the citizens of each state or territory are represented by their elected heads, and the smaller states have equal representation. A forum such as the national cabinet is open to criticism as undemocratic, as the role of the [[Australian Parliament]] is put to one side. However, the National Cabinet is based on negotiation and compromise among the states, rather than the will of the majority. Parliament is suspended rather than [[prorogue]]d (dissolved); Parliament will pass legislation based on decisions made by the National Cabinet. Once the crisis has passed, all decisions taken by the Cabinet will fall under the scrutiny of normal democratic processes and thus be accountable for all decisions taken.<ref name=menziesconv/>\n\n==Current membership==\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n!Name!!Office held!!In office since!!colspan=\"2\"|Party\n|-\n|[[Scott Morrison]] [[Australian House of Representatives|MP]]\n|[[Prime Minister of Australia|Prime Minister]] of Australia\n|{{dts|2018|08|24|format=dmy}}\n| {{Australian party style|Liberal}}|&nbsp;\n|[[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]]\n|-\n|[[Gladys Berejiklian]] [[New South Wales Legislative Assembly|MP]]\n|[[Premier of New South Wales|Premier]] of [[New South Wales]]\n|{{dts|2017|01|23|format=dmy}}\n| {{Australian party style|Liberal}}|&nbsp;\n|[[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]]\n|-\n|[[Daniel Andrews]] [[Victorian Legislative Assembly|MP]]\n|[[Premier of Victoria|Premier]] of [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]\n|{{dts|2014|12|4|format=dmy}}\n| {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp;\n|[[Australian Labor Party|Labor]]\n|-\n|[[Annastacia Palaszczuk]] [[Legislative Assembly of Queensland|MP]]\n|[[Premier of Queensland|Premier]] of [[Queensland]]\n|{{dts|2015|2|14|format=dmy}}\n| {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp;\n|[[Australian Labor Party|Labor]]\n|-\n|[[Mark McGowan]] [[Western Australian Legislative Assembly|MLA]]\n|[[Premier of Western Australia|Premier]] of [[Western Australia]] \n|{{dts|2017|03|17|format=dmy}}\n| {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp;\n|[[Australian Labor Party|Labor]]\n|-\n|[[Steven Marshall]] [[South Australian House of Assembly|MP]]\n|[[Premier of South Australia|Premier]] of [[South Australia]]\n|{{dts|2018|3|19|format=dmy}}\n| {{Australian party style|Liberal}}|&nbsp;\n|[[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]]\n|-\n|[[Peter Gutwein]] [[Tasmanian House of Assembly|MHA]]\n|[[Premier of Tasmania|Premier]] of [[Tasmania]]\n|{{dts|2020|01|20|format=dmy}}\n| {{Australian party style|Liberal}}|&nbsp;\n|[[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal]]\n|-\n|[[Andrew Barr]] [[Australian Capital Territory Legislative Assembly|MLA]]\n|[[Chief Minister of the Australian Capital Territory|Chief Minister]] of the [[Australian Capital Territory]]\n|{{dts|2014|12|11|format=dmy}}\n| {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp;\n|[[Australian Labor Party|Labor]]\n|-\n|[[Michael Gunner]] [[Northern Territory Legislative Assembly|MLA]]\n|[[Chief Minister of the Northern Territory|Chief Minister]] of the [[Northern Territory]]\n|{{dts|2016|8|31|format=dmy}}\n| {{Australian party style|Labor}}|&nbsp;\n|[[Australian Labor Party|Labor]]\n|}\n\n==Meetings and press releases==\n*16 March 2020: Announcement of a \"significant step-up\" to the pandemic, upon the advice of the AHPPC, with additional measures in order to reduce community transmission. These included banning [[cruise ship]]s from docking, enhanced screening of arrivals, and mandatory [[self-isolation]] for everyone arriving in Australia. The Cabinet also activated the second stage of the ''Australian Health Sector Emergency Response Plan for Novel Coronavirus'', which \"enables governments to undertake targeted action... and ensures that resources are properly allocated where needed and the risks to vulnerable people in the community are mitigated\".<ref>{{cite web | title=Coronavirus measures endorsed by National Cabinet | website=Prime Minister of Australia | url=https://www.pm.gov.au/media/coronavirus-measures-endorsed-national-cabinet | access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n*25 March 2020: PM announces creation of the [[National COVID-19 Coordination Commission]] (NCCC), and clarifies role of various bodies: the National Cabinet \"continues to lead the national response at a government level. The National Security Committee of Cabinet\u2019s COVID-19 Taskforce and the Expenditure Review Committee of Cabinet continue to take decisions that determine the Commonwealth\u2019s response to the global COVID-19 pandemic\".<ref>{{cite web | title=National Covid-19 Coordination Commission | website=Prime Minister of Australia | url=https://www.pm.gov.au/media/national-covid-19-coordination-commission | access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n*29 March 2020: The Cabinet noted that the rate of increase of the spread of COVID-19 was slowing, but overall numbers were still increasing and welcomed the new coronavirus [[app]] and [[WhatsApp]] channel released by the Government. It announced new limits to indoor and outdoor gatherings to two persons only (with some exceptions); discussed further [[social distancing]] measures; gave further advice to [[senior citizens]]; and agreed to a [[moratorium]] on [[eviction]]s for the coming six months for both commercial and residential [[tenancies]] suffering financial distress.<ref name=mr20mar>{{cite web | title=National Cabinet Statement | website=Prime Minister of Australia | url=https://www.pm.gov.au/media/national-cabinet-statement  | access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Cabinet of Australia]]\n* [[Council of Australian Governments]]\n* [[Loan Council]]\n* [[National Security Committee (Australia)|National Security Committee]]\n* [[War cabinet#Australia|War Cabinet of Australia]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n\n{{Politics of Australia}}\n\n[[Category:Government of Australia]]\n[[Category:Council of Australian Governments]]\n[[Category:2020 in Australia]]\n", "name_user": "Laterthanyouthink", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMeetings and press releases:add link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Cabinet_of_Australia"}
{"title_page": "Minimum deviation", "text_new": "[[File: Deviation angle of a beam of light entering a medium with refractive index.png|thumb|Light is deflected as it enters a material with refractive index >&nbsp;1.]]\n[[File: Deflection of light ray passing through prism.png|thumb|A ray of light is deflected twice in a prism. The sum of these deflections is the deviation angle.]]\n[[File: Minimum deflection of light ray passing through prism.png|thumb|When the entrance and exit angles are equal, the deviation angle of a ray passing through a prism will be minimal.]]\n\nIn a [[prism]], the angle of deviation(<math> \\delta</math>) decreases with increase in the angle of incidence(<math> i</math>) up to a particular angle. This angle of incidence where the angle of deviation in a prism is minimum is called the '''minimum deviation position''' of the prism and that very deviation angle is known as the '''minimum angle of deviation''' (denoted by <math> \\delta_{min}</math> or <math> D_{\\lambda}</math>).\n\nIt may be noted that minimum deviation in a '''rectangular slab''' is '''zero''', as both the surfaces separating two media are parallel, whereas in a prism they are inclined to each other.\n\nOne of the factors that causes a rainbow is the bunching of light rays at the minimum deviation angle that is close to the '''rainbow angle.''' (For more information, see the sub-heading 'Mathematical Deduction' in [[rainbow]] article.)\n\n==Factors==\n\nThe deviation angle in a prism depends upon:\n\n# '''Refractive index of the prism'''(<math> n</math>)''':''' The larger the [[refractive index]], the larger the deviation angle.\n# '''Angle of the prism'''(<math> A</math>): The larger the prism angle, the larger the deviation angle.\n# '''Angle of incidence'''(<math> i</math>): The deviation angle first increases with increasing incidence angle and then decreases.\n\nAll these factors are quite evident from the formula it the next section.\n\n==Equation and Graph==\n\nFor minimum deviation the following conditions hold:\n\n\u2022 The refracted ray in the prism is '''parallel''' to its base. In other words, the light ray is '''symmetrical''' about thr axis of symmetry of the prism.\n\u00a0\n\u00a0<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.a-levelphysicstutor.com/optics-prisms.php|title=A-Level Physics Tutor|last=|first=|date=|website=A-Level Physics Tutor|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n\u2022 [[Angle of incidence (optics)|Angle of incidence]] and angle of emergence are equal. i = e\n\n\u2022 Angles of refractions are also equal i.e. r<sub>1</sub> = r<sub>2.</sub>\n\n\nWe know, i + e = \u03b4 + A\n\nSo, 2i = \u03b4<sub>min</sub> + A\n\ni = (\u03b4<sub>min</sub> + A) / 2\n\nAlso, r = A/2\n\nFrom the [[Snell's law|Snell's laws]],\n\nn = sin i / sin r\n\n:<math>n_ = \\frac{\\sin(\\frac{A + \\delta_{min}}{2})}{\\sin(\\frac{A}{2})},</math><ref name=\":0\" />\n:\n\n\n\nThis is a convenient way to measure the refractive index of a prism by directing a light ray through the prism such that it produces the minimum deviation angle.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mtholyoke.edu/~mpeterso/classes/phys103/geomopti/MinDev.html|title=Minimum Deviation by a Prism|last=Mark A. Peterson|publisher=[[Mount Holyoke College]]}}</ref>\n\nEg: The refractive index of glass is 1.5. Find the minimum angle of deviation for an equilateral triangle.\n\nSol:\n\nHere,\n\nA = 60\u00b0, n = 1.5\n\nPutting them in the above formula,\n\nsin{(60 + \u03b4)/2}/sin(60/2) = 1.5\n\nor, sin(30 + \u03b4/2)/sin(30) = 1.5\n\nor, sin(30 + \u03b4/2) = 1.5 \u00d7 0.5\n\nor, 30 + \u03b4/2 = arcsin(0.75)\n\nor, \u03b4/2 = 48.6 - 30\n\nor, \u03b4 = 2 \u00d7 18.6\n\nSo, \u03b4 ~ 37\u00b0\n\n:\n\nAlso, the variation of angle of deviation with an arbitrary angle of incidence can be encapsulated into a single equation:\n\n:<math>\\delta = i - A + \\arcsin\\left(n \\cdot \\sin\\left(A - \\arcsin\\left(\\frac{\\sin i}{n}\\right)\\right)\\right),</math>\n\n==References==\n<references/><br />\n[[Category:Optics]]\n", "text_old": "[[File: Deviation angle of a beam of light entering a medium with refractive index.png|thumb|Light is deflected as it enters a material with refractive index >&nbsp;1.]]\n[[File: Deflection of light ray passing through prism.png|thumb|A ray of light is deflected twice in a prism. The sum of these deflections is the deviation angle.]]\n[[File: Minimum deflection of light ray passing through prism.png|thumb|When the entrance and exit angles are equal, the deviation angle of a ray passing through a prism will be minimal.]]\n\nIn a [[prism]], the angle of deviation(<math> \\delta</math>) decreases with increase in the angle of incidence(<math> i</math>) up to a particular angle. This angle of incidence where the angle of deviation in a prism is minimum is called the '''minimum deviation position''' of the prism and that very deviation angle is known as the '''minimum angle of deviation''' (denoted by <math> \\delta_{min}</math> or <math> D_{\\lambda}</math>).\n\nIt may be noted that minimum deviation in a '''rectangular slab''' is '''zero''', as both the surfaces separating two media are parallel, whereas in a prism they are inclined to each other.\n\nOne of the factors that causes a [[rainbow]] is the bunching of light rays at the minimum deviation angle that is close to the '''rainbow angle'''.\n\n==Factors==\n\nThe deviation angle in a prism depends upon:\n\n# '''Refractive index of the prism'''(<math> n</math>)''':''' The larger the [[refractive index]], the larger the deviation angle.\n# '''Angle of the prism'''(<math> A</math>): The larger the prism angle, the larger the deviation angle.\n# '''Angle of incidence'''(<math> i</math>): The deviation angle first increases with increasing incidence angle and then decreases.\n\nAll these factors are quite evident from the formula it the next section.\n\n==Equation and Graph==\n\nFor minimum deviation the following conditions hold:\n\n\u2022 The refracted ray in the prism is '''parallel''' to its base. In other words, the light ray is '''symmetrical''' about thr axis of symmetry of the prism.\n\u00a0\n\u00a0<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.a-levelphysicstutor.com/optics-prisms.php|title=A-Level Physics Tutor|last=|first=|date=|website=A-Level Physics Tutor|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n\u2022 [[Angle of incidence (optics)|Angle of incidence]] and angle of emergence are equal. i = e\n\n\u2022 Angles of refractions are also equal i.e. r<sub>1</sub> = r<sub>2.</sub>\n\n\nWe know, i + e = \u03b4 + A\n\nSo, 2i = \u03b4<sub>min</sub> + A\n\ni = (\u03b4<sub>min</sub> + A) / 2\n\nAlso, r = A/2\n\nFrom the [[Snell's law|Snell's laws]],\n\nn = sin i / sin r\n\n:<math>n_ = \\frac{\\sin(\\frac{A + \\delta_{min}}{2})}{\\sin(\\frac{A}{2})},</math><ref name=\":0\" />\n:\n\n\n\nThis is a convenient way to measure the refractive index of a prism by directing a light ray through the prism such that it produces the minimum deviation angle.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mtholyoke.edu/~mpeterso/classes/phys103/geomopti/MinDev.html|title=Minimum Deviation by a Prism|last=Mark A. Peterson|publisher=[[Mount Holyoke College]]}}</ref>\n\nEg: The refractive index of glass is 1.5. Find the minimum angle of deviation for an equilateral triangle.\n\nSol:\n\nHere,\n\nA = 60\u00b0, n = 1.5\n\nPutting them in the above formula,\n\nsin{(60 + \u03b4)/2}/sin(60/2) = 1.5\n\nor, sin(30 + \u03b4/2)/sin(30) = 1.5\n\nor, sin(30 + \u03b4/2) = 1.5 \u00d7 0.5\n\nor, 30 + \u03b4/2 = arcsin(0.75)\n\nor, \u03b4/2 = 48.6 - 30\n\nor, \u03b4 = 2 \u00d7 18.6\n\nSo, \u03b4 ~ 37\u00b0\n\n:\n\nAlso, the variation of angle of deviation with an arbitrary angle of incidence can be encapsulated into a single equation:\n\n:<math>\\delta = i - A + \\arcsin\\left(n \\cdot \\sin\\left(A - \\arcsin\\left(\\frac{\\sin i}{n}\\right)\\right)\\right),</math>\n\n==References==\n<references/><br />\n[[Category:Optics]]\n", "name_user": "Shubhrajit Sadhukhan", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minimum_deviation"}
{"title_page": "When I Grow Up (The Pussycat Dolls song)", "text_new": "{{short description|2008 single by The Pussycat Dolls}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = When I Grow Up\n| cover      = When I Grow Up.png\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[The Pussycat Dolls]]\n| album      = [[Doll Domination]]\n| released   = {{Start date|2008|05|27}}\n| format     = \n*[[CD single|CD]]\n*[[12-inch single|12\"]]\n*[[music download|digital download]]\n| recorded   = 2007&ndash;2008\n| studio     = \n*2nd Floor Studios (Orlando)\n*[[Chalice Recording Studios|Chalice Studios]] (Los Angeles)\n| genre      = [[Electropop]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=4|s=05}}\n| label      = [[Interscope Records|Interscope]]\n| writer     = \n*[[Rodney Jerkins|Rodney \"Darkchild\" Jerkins]]\n*[[Rock City (production duo)|Theron Thomas]]\n*[[Rock City (production duo)|Timothy Thomas]]\n*[[Jim McCarty]]\n*[[Paul Samwell-Smith]]\n| producer   = Darkchild\n| prev_title = [[Wait a Minute (The Pussycat Dolls song)|Wait a Minute]]\n| prev_year  = 2006\n| next_title = [[Whatcha Think About That]]\n| next_year  = 2008\n}}\n\n\"'''When I Grow Up'''\" is a song by American [[girl group]] [[The Pussycat Dolls]] from their second and final studio album ''[[Doll Domination]]'' (2008). It was released by [[Interscope Records]] on May 27, 2008, as the [[lead single]] from the album. \"When I Grow Up\" was their first single following the departure of the group's longest-standing member [[Carmit Bachar]]. The song was originally written with [[Britney Spears]] in mind, but her label rejected it. It was first recorded for [[Nicole Scherzinger]]'s planned solo project, ''Her Name Is Nicole'', but after its cancellation and Scherzinger's return to the group, she felt that the song was better suited for the group. It was written by Theron Thomas, Timothy Thomas and [[Rodney Jerkins|Rodney \"Darkchild\" Jerkins]], who also produced the song. It is an uptempo [[electropop]] song. It samples the 1966 song, \"He's Always There\" by British rock band [[The Yardbirds]]. \"When I Grow Up\" speaks about the desire to be famous, and was described as being \"autobiographical\" by Scherzinger.\n\nThe single was received favorably by contemporary music critics, many of whom highlighted it as a stand-out. It peaked at number nine on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], becoming the group's highest charting single since \"[[Buttons (The Pussycat Dolls song)|Buttons]]\" (2006). The song has sold over two million digital copies in the United States, making the Pussycat Dolls the first female group in digital history to have three singles pass the two million mark in digital sales. The song reached the top-five in countries such as Australia, Canada, France, Ireland, New Zealand and the United Kingdom, and the top-ten in Austria, Denmark, Germany and Switzerland.\n\nThe song's accompanying music video premiered on June 13, 2008. Directed by [[Joseph Khan]], it portrays the Pussycat Dolls in a traffic jam on [[Hollywood Boulevard]]. It was complimented for its dance breakdown, and was nominated in five categories at the [[2008 MTV Video Music Awards]], the most of that ceremony, and went on to win [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Dance Video|Best Dance Video]]. The Pussycat Dolls performed the song on television shows including ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'' and ''[[So You Think You Can Dance (U.S. TV series)|So You Think You Can Dance]]'', as well several award shows including the [[2008 American Music Awards]], and throughout their [[Doll Domination Tour]] (2009).\n\n== Background ==\n[[File:Nicole Scherzinger 2007.jpg|Lead singer [[Nicole Scherzinger]] ''(pictured)'' originally recorded \"When I Grow Up\" for her unreleased solo album ''Her Name Is Nicole'', but felt the song was more suitable for the Pussycat Dolls.<ref name=\"Nicole Scherzinger PCD Interview\"/>|180px|alt=|thumb|left]]\n\nFollowing the commercial success of ''[[PCD (album)|PCD]]'' (2005),<ref>{{cite web|last=Moss |first=Corey |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1543692/pussycat-doll-nicole-grabs-timbaland-akon-lp.jhtml |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64I4eXATX?url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1543692/pussycat-doll-nicole-grabs-timbaland-akon-lp.jhtml |archivedate=December 29, 2011 |title=Pussycat Doll Nicole Snares Timbaland, Will.I.Am for Solo LP |work=MTV |publisher=[[MTV Networks]] |date=October 23, 2006 |accessdate=September 25, 2011}}</ref> and over the course of two years (2005\u201307),<ref>{{cite web|last=Surette |first=Tim |url=http://www.tv.com/shows/pussycat-dolls-present/ |title=Pussycat Dolls Present |publisher=TV.com |accessdate=December 30, 2011}}</ref> Scherzinger recorded 75-100 songs for ''Her Name Is Nicole'', her planned solo debut album.<ref name=\"Bio\"/>  Her work as lead singer furthered Scherzinger's popularity as she began work on her own music.<ref>{{cite web |first=Emmanuel |last=Ezugwu |url=http://allhiphop.com/2007/12/03/nicole-scherzinger-remember-the-name |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64I4oinP6?url=http://allhiphop.com/2007/12/03/nicole-scherzinger-remember-the-name/ |archivedate=December 29, 2011 |title=Nicole Scherzinger: Remember the Name |publisher=Allhiphop |date=December 3, 2007 |accessdate=September 21, 2009}}</ref> She stated that she enjoyed collaborating with many different artists, and that although she had been writing songs for over ten years, she felt as if she was at a different level while working with such [[A-list]] writers and producers.<ref name=\"Bio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hernameisnicole.com/-/Main.aspx?pbt_name=Bio |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071225185024/http://www.hernameisnicole.com/-/Main.aspx?pbt_name=Bio |archivedate=December 25, 2007 |title= Nicole's Biography |publisher=[[Interscope Records]] |accessdate=September 21, 2009}}</ref> Following the moderate success of \"[[Baby Love (Nicole Scherzinger song)|Baby Love]]\", the complete lack of success of the singles such as \"[[Whatever U Like]]\" and numerous delays, Scherzinger decided to halt production on her debut album.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://idolator.com/5053295/her-name-is-nicole-exists-sort-of |title='Her Name Is Nicole' Exists, Sort Of |author=Maura |date=September 22, 2008 |accessdate=February 13, 2011 |publisher=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]. [[Buzz Media]]}}</ref> She then returned her focus back on the Pussycat Dolls, and recording commenced for their second studio album.<ref name=\"Nicole Scherzinger PCD Interview\">{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/news/nicole-scherzinger/42231-nicole-scherzinger-pcd-interview |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64I5ZeCc7?url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/news/nicole-scherzinger/42231-nicole-scherzinger-pcd-interview |archivedate=December 29, 2011 |title=Nicole Scherzinger PCD Interview |work=[[MTV UK]] |publisher=MTV Networks |date=August 18, 2008 |accessdate=May 9, 2010}}</ref> Scherzinger cited that she felt as if the songs were more suited as a Pussycat Dolls song than her own.<ref name=\"Nicole Scherzinger PCD Interview\"/>\n\n{{Quote box|width=27%|align=right|quote=\"For me it was what I wanted to do. I'm a relentless perfectionist and I realised that a lot of the songs from my record should be Pussycat Dolls songs including 'When I Grow Up'. Next year I want to put out my solo album and I think the two will be able to co-exist nicely together.\"|source=\u2014Scherzinger on why she halted production of her solo album.<ref name=\"Nicole Scherzinger PCD Interview\"/>}}\n\n\"When I Grow Up\" was written by [[Rock City (production duo)|Theron and Timothy Thomas]], along with [[Rodney Jerkins|Rodney \"Darkchild\" Jerkins]], who also produced the song.<ref name=\"bmi\">{{cite web|url=http://repertoire.bmi.com/title.asp?blnWriter=True&blnPublisher=True&blnArtist=True&page=1&keyid=9778100&ShowNbr=0&ShowSeqNbr=0&querytype=WorkID|title='When I Grow Up' BMI Work #9778100 |accessdate=May 8, 2010 |publisher=BMI Repertoire ([[Broadcast Music Incorporated]])}}</ref> The song was originally written with [[Britney Spears]] in mind, and a [[Demo (music)|demo]] recorded by [[Wayne Hector]] was pitched for her fifth studio album ''[[Blackout (Britney Spears album)|Blackout]]'' (2007), but her label rejected it and the song was never recorded by Spears.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/rhys-glover-1/when-i-grow-up-demo-for-britney-spears|title=Wayne Hector - When I Grow Up (Demo for Britney Spears)|accessdate=March 15, 2018|publisher=[[SoundCloud]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://muumuse.com/2011/01/daily-b-how-would-the-pussycat-dolls-when-i-grow-up-sound-if-britney-sang-it.html/|title=Daily B: How Would The Pussycat Dolls' \"When I Grow Up\" Sound if Britney Sang It?|date=January 17, 2011|accessdate=March 15, 2018|author=Bradley Stern|publisher=[[MuuMuse]]}}</ref>\n\nWhen the song was given to Scherzinger, and eventually the Pussycat Dolls, it was reworked and recorded by Paul Foley, Mike \"Handz\" Donaldson and Roberto \"Tito\" Vazquez at 2nd Floor Studios in [[Orlando]] and [[Chalice Recording Studios|Chalice Studios]] in Los Angeles, and was mixed by [[Spike Stent]] and\nRodney \"Darkchild\" Jerkins at Chalice Studios in Los Angeles.<ref name=\"Album Notes\"/> [[The Yardbirds]]' drummer [[Jim McCarty]] and bassist [[Paul Samwell-Smith]] both received co-writing credits for the song, for its sample of \"He's Always There\" (1966).<ref name=\"Album Notes\">{{cite AV media notes |title=Doll Domination |titlelink=Doll Domination |others=Pussycat Dolls |year=2008 |authorlink=Pussycat Dolls |type=Compact Disc |publisher=Interscope Records |location=Santa Monica, California}}</ref> \"When I Grow Up\" made its world premiere online on May 16, 2008,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2008/05/16/pussycat-dolls-to-debut-new-single-may-20 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64I5pTbOH?url=http://www.rap-up.com/2008/05/16/pussycat-dolls-to-debut-new-single-may-20/ |archivedate=December 29, 2011 |title=Pussycat Dolls to Debut New Single May 20 |date=May 16, 2008 |work=[[Rap-Up]] |publisher=Devine Lazerine|accessdate=September 4, 2011}}</ref> and was issued as a [[music download|digital download]] in North America on May 27.<ref name=\"NA digital\">{{cite web|url=http://www.interscope.com/artist/releases/detail.aspx?pid=1328&aid=455 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64I6082ww?url=http://www.interscope.com/artist/releases/detail.aspx?pid=1328&aid=455 |archivedate=December 29, 2011 |title=When I Grow Up |publisher=Interscope Records |accessdate=November 27, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It was later serviced to [[contemporary hit radio]] in the United States on June 1, 2008.<ref name=\"radioandrecords1\">{{cite magazine|url=http://gfa.radioandrecords.com/publishGFA/GFANextPage.asp?sDate=06/01/2008&Format=1 |title=Going For Adds: CHR/Top 40 |date=January 6, 2008 |accessdate=November 27, 2010 |magazine=[[Radio & Records]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715144504/http://gfa.radioandrecords.com/publishGFA/GFANextPage.asp?sDate=06%2F01%2F2008&Format=1 |archivedate=July 15, 2011 }}</ref> The release of \"When I Grow Up\" came after the departure of member [[Carmit Bachar]]. It was officially confirmed, after months of speculation, on March 4, 2008 that Bachar had left the group to follow \"other performance interests\". At the time of her departure, she had been the longest member of the group, joining in 1995 when they were a [[American burlesque|burlesque act]].<ref name=\"Fletcher\">{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/news/a90760/pussycat-doll-bachar-quits-group.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64I6BXw1H?url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/news/a90760/pussycat-doll-bachar-quits-group.html |archivedate=December 29, 2011 |title=Pussycat Doll Bachar quits group |publisher=[[Digital Spy]]. [[Hachette Filipacchi M\u00e9dias]] |last=Fletcher |first=Adam |date=September 5, 2008|accessdate=September 5, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Composition ==\n{{listen|filename= PCD - WIGU.ogg|title=\"When I Grow Up\"|description=A 24-second sample of the chorus of \"When I Grow Up\", which features the Pussycat Dolls lead singer Nicole Scherzinger expressing a crave for fame, while later warning the listener of the \"high cost\" of it.<ref name=\"mtvnews\"/>|pos=right|format=[[Ogg]]}}\n\n\"When I Grow Up\" is an uptempo [[electropop]] song<ref name=\"Sputnikmusic\">{{cite news|url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/32066/Pussycat-Dolls-Doll-Domination|title=Pussycat Dolls \u2013 Doll Domination (staff review) |last=Klapper |first=Rudy |date=August 25, 2009 |accessdate=August 4, 2011 |publisher= [[Sputnikmusic]] (Jeremy Ferwerda)}}</ref> that lasts four minutes and five seconds.<ref name=\"Album Notes\"/> Built around \"bouncy synth lines\" and a \"thudding\" [[bassline]],<ref name=\"Sputnikmusic\"/> the song features a heavy use of sirens, handclaps and pitch-shifted vocals.<ref name=\"mtvnews\">{{cite news |last1=Montgomery |first1=James |last2=Stolz |first2=Kim |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1588426/pussycat-dolls-rehearse-mtv-movie-awards.jhtml |title=Pussycat Dolls Prepare for MTV Movie Awards Performance \u2013 And 'The Next Level' |publisher=MTV News. MTV Networks |date=May 31, 2008 |accessdate=December 27, 2010}}</ref> Scherzinger was cited as adopting [[Britney Spears]]' breathiness against the song's sirens, shouts and \"pumping beat\".<ref name=\"Nytimes\">{{cite web|last=Pareles |first=Jon |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=990CE1DE103DF931A1575AC0A96E9C8B63 |title=Critics' Choice |work=[[New York Times]]|date=September 22, 2008 |accessdate=December 30, 2011}}</ref> Jaime Gill from [[Yahoo Music|Yahoo Music UK]] described \"When I Grow Up\" as a \"dark, dissonant club banger\",<ref>{{cite news|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081001164527/http://uk.launch.yahoo.com/080924/33/21zwb.html|archivedate=October 1, 2008|url=http://uk.launch.yahoo.com/080924/33/21zwb.html|title=Pussycat Dolls \u2013 Doll Domination \u2013 Album Review|last=Gill|first=Jaime|date=September 24, 2008|accessdate=November 1, 2010|publisher=[[Yahoo! Music|Yahoo Music UK]] [[Yahoo!]]}}</ref> while Rudy Klapper from [[Sputnikmusic]] compared the song's composition to that of [[Basement Jaxx]]'s 2003 track \"[[Plug It In (song)|Plug It In]]\".<ref name=\"Sputnikmusic\"/> \"When I Grow Up\" contains a sample of the main [[riff (music)|riff]] of \"He's Always There\" by British rock band The Yardbirds, from their third studio album ''[[Roger the Engineer]]'' (1966).<ref name=\"Album Notes\"/> The song's writers, Jim McCarty and Paul Samwell-Smith, were honored for their contributions to the song at the [[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers]] (ASCAP).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/267059/mccartney-coldplay-honored-at-ascap-awards|title=McCartney, Coldplay Honored At ASCAP Awards|last=Paine|first=Andre|date=November 14, 2009|work=Billboard|accessdate=September 21, 2011|location=London}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[sheet music]] published by [[Sony/ATV Music Publishing]], \"When I Grow Up\" is set in [[time signature|common time]] with a tempo of 120 [[beats per minute]]. It is composed in the key of [[E minor]], with Scherzinger's vocal range spanning from low-note of E<sub>3</sub> to the high-note of G<sub>5</sub>.<ref name=\"music\">{{cite web|url=http://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtdVPE.asp?ppn=MN0067375|author=Theron Thomas, Jim McCarty, Paul Samwell-Smith, Timothy Thomas, Rodney Jerkins (Composers and Lyricists)|title=Pussycat Dolls \u2013 When I Grow Up Sheet Music (Digital Download)|year=2008|accessdate=September 25, 2011|work=Musicnotes.com|publisher=[[Alfred Music Publishing]]|format=Musicnotes|at=MN0067375 (Product Number)}}</ref> Lyrically, the song is centered around the desire to be famous when one grows up.<ref name=\"Perkins\"/> Using satirical and autobiographical lines, Scherzinger begins the song's first verse with: \"Now I've got a confession / When I was young I wanted attention\".<ref name=\"Perkins\"/><ref name=\"Digispy\"/> The \"repetitive and catchy chorus\" follows, where she sings the lines: \"When I grow up / I wanna be famous / I wanna be a star / I wanna be in movies\".<ref name=\"mtvnews\"/><ref name=\"Perkins\"/> [[MTV News]] commented that the song contains a theme that is \"getting plenty of traction these days \u2013 beware the high cost of fame.\"<ref name=\"mtvnews\"/> Meanwhile, group member [[Melody Thornton]] said of the song's concept: \"If you strive for higher and bigger things \u2013 along with that \u2013 comes hard work and dealing with a lot of stuff that you'd never assume you'd have to. So yeah, while the song is meant to be playful, it still does have that little warning twist to it\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bluesandsoul.com/feature/332/perrrfect_placement/|title=Pussycat Dolls \u2013 Hello Dolly|work=[[Blues & Soul]]|last=Lewis|first=Pete|accessdate=October 24, 2010}}</ref> Bill Lamb from [[About.com]] named \"When I Grow Up\" a possible [[answer song]] to [[Pink (singer)|Pink]]'s \"[[Stupid Girls]]\" (2006).<ref name=\"Lamb\">{{cite news|url=http://top40.about.com/od/singles/gr/pussycatdollswh.htm|title=Review of the single \"When I Grow Up\" by the Pussycat Dolls|publisher=[[About.com]]. The New York Times Company|last=Lamb |first=Bill|date=May 27, 2008 |accessdate=November 5, 2010}}</ref> Music critics were initially confused by the line \"I wanna have [[groupie]]s\" in the chorus; mistaking the line as saying \"I wanna have [[breast|boobies]]\".<ref name=\"Perkins\"/> American comedian [[Ellen DeGeneres]] also pointed this out when they performed the song on her [[The Ellen DeGeneres Show|talk show]] on September 23, 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ellen.warnerbros.com/2008/09/boobies_or_groupies.php|title=Do the Pussycat Dolls Want 'Boobies' or 'Groupies'? Ellen Gets the Scoop!|publisher=[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]] ([[Warner Bros.]])|date=September 23, 2008|accessdate=October 24, 2010}}</ref> Nicole Scherzinger said that \"All of us started with a dream...I know when I was young, and I would sign people's notebooks, I wrote, 'Remember me when I'm famous,' and I don't know of a little kid who hasn't aspired to be someone\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.songfacts.com/detail.php?id=11929 |title=Nicole Scherzinger explains the song |last= |first=|date= |access-date=August 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Remixes ==\nA number of remixes were commissioned by [[Interscope Records]] to accompany the song. On July 23, 2008 a remix of \"When I Grow Up\" featuring a rap verse from American rapper [[Eve (entertainer)|Eve]] was released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2008/07/23/new-music-pussycat-dolls-f-eve-when-i-grow-up-remix |title=New Music: Pussycat Dolls f/ Eve \u2013 'When I Grow Up (Remix)' |work=Rap-Up |publisher=Devine Lazerine|date=July 23, 2008 |accessdate=September 25, 2011}}</ref> Later that same day, a second remix was released online.<ref name=\"Darkchild Remix\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2008/07/23/new-music-pussycat-dolls-when-i-grow-up-darkchild-remix |title=New Music: Pussycat Dolls \u2013 'When I Grow Up (Darkchild Remix)' |work=Rap-Up |publisher=Devine Lazerine|date=July 23, 2008 |accessdate=September 25, 2011}}</ref> Entitled the \"Darkchild Remix\", it features an entirely different beat than the original, with added vocals from American rappers Diddy, [[Lil Wayne]] and [[Fatman Scoop]], as well as the song's producer Rodney \"Darkchild\" Jerkins.<ref name=\"Darkchild Remix\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.djbooth.net/index/tracks/review/pussycat-dolls-ft-diddy-rock-city-fatman-scoop-when-i-grow-up-remix |title=Pussycat Dolls ft. Diddy, Rock City & Fatman Scoop \u2013 When I Grow Up (Remix) \u2013 Listen Now |publisher=DjBooth|accessdate=December 30, 2011}}</ref> Elements of [[Michael Jackson]]'s \"[[Thriller (song)|Thriller]]\" (1984) were heavily sampled throughout the remix, most noticeably in the song's introduction.<ref name=\"Darkchild Remix\"/> Lil Wayne's verse was later removed and replaced by a new verse by the song's composers, Rock City, due to issues with it being cleared in time for its commercial release as a B-side to \"[[Whatcha Think About That]]\", the second single from ''Doll Domination''.<ref name=\"Darkchild vlog\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2008/09/24/darkchild-vlog-2-remixing-the-pussycat-dolls-a-darkchild-album |title=Darkchild Vlog #2: Remixing the Pussycat Dolls; A Darkchild Album? |work=Rap-Up |publisher=Devine Lazerine|date=September 24, 2008 |accessdate=December 30, 2011}}</ref> For unknown reasons, the remix was never released. Additional \"club\" and \"dub\" remixes of \"When I Grow Up\" by DJs [[Dave Aud\u00e9]], [[Digital Dog]], [[Dirty South (DJ)|Dirty South]] and [[Ralphi Rosario]], and the electronic band [[Wideboys]] were also released in a series of Compact Disc single and digital download releases.<ref name=\"US Remixes single\">{{cite AV media notes|title=When I Grow Up (Remixes) |others=Pussycat Dolls|date=2008|type=US Remixes CD single liner notes|publisher=Interscope Records|id=LC06406}}</ref><ref name=\"FR digital EP\"/>\n\n== Commercial performance ==\nIn the United States, the song debuted on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] at number 76 on the issue dated June 14, 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1045170/lil-wayne-fends-off-coldplay-perry-on-hot-100|title=Lil Wayne Fends Off Coldplay, Perry On Hot 100|last=Cohen|first=Jonathan|date=May 8, 2008|work=Billboard|accessdate=October 31, 2010}}</ref> On its second week, the song sold 34,000 digital downloads and ascended to number 31.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1045104/lil-wayne-continues-hot-100-dominance|title=Lil Wayne Continues Hot 100 Dominance|last=Cohen|first=Jonathan|date=May 12, 2008|work=Billboard|accessdate=October 31, 2010}}</ref> In its fourth week, it reached its peak position of number nine, becoming the group's highest charting single since \"[[Buttons (The Pussycat Dolls song)|Buttons]]\" which peaked at number three in 2006.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1044966/katy-perry-scores-1000th-no-1-hit-of-rock-era|title=Katy Perry Scores 1,000th No. 1 Hit Of Rock Era|last=Cohen|first=Jonathan|date=June 26, 2008|work=Billboard|accessdate=September 26, 2014}}</ref> The song topped the [[Hot Dance Club Songs|Hot Dance Club Play]] chart, the issue dated August 2, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2008-08-02/dance-club-play-songs|title=Billboard Hot Dance Club Songs Week of August 2, 2008|date=August 2, 2008|accessdate=October 31, 2010|work=Billboard}}</ref> The song has sold over 2.18 million digital downloads in the United States to date, according to Nielsen Soundscan, making the Pussycat Dolls the first all-female group in digital history to have three singles\u2014along with \"Don't Cha\" and \"Buttons\"\u2014pass the two million mark in digital sales.<ref name=PaulGrein>{{cite web|url=http://music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart-watch/week-ending-jan-24-2010-hope-for-haiti-makes-history.html |title=Week Ending Jan. 24, 2010: Hope For Haiti Makes History |last=Grein |first=Paul |date=January 27, 2010 |publisher=[[Yahoo! Music]]. Yahoo! |accessdate=November 18, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121002142924/http://music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart-watch/week-ending-jan-24-2010-hope-for-haiti-makes-history.html |archivedate=October 2, 2012 }}</ref> In Canada, the song debuted at number fifteen on the [[Canadian Hot 100]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2008-06-14/canadian-hot-100?order=gainer|title=Canadian Hot 100|date=June 14, 2008|accessdate=October 31, 2010|work=Billboard}}</ref> On the chart dated September 6, 2008, \"When I Grow Up\" ascended and peaked at number three.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2008-09-06/canadian-hot-100|title=Canadian Hot 100|date=September 6, 2008|accessdate=October 31, 2010|work=Billboard}}</ref>\n\nIn Australia, the song debuted at number 45, on June 22, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/weekchart.asp?cat=s&year=2008&date=20080622|title=Australia Singles Top 50(22/06/2008)|date=June 22, 2010|publisher= [[ARIA Charts]]. [[Australian Recording Industry Association]]|accessdate=October 31, 2010}}</ref> In its sixth week, the song peaked at number two and stayed there for three consecutive weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/weekchart.asp?cat=s&year=2008&date=20080810|title=Australia Singles Top 50(10/08/2008)|date=August 10, 2010|publisher= ARIA Charts. Australian Recording Industry Association|accessdate=October 31, 2010}}</ref> \"When I Grow Up\" was certified [[music recording sales certifications|platinum]] by the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] (ARIA) for shipments of 70,000 copies.<ref name=aria>{{cite web|url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupageshttpwww.aria.com.aupagesARIACharts-Accreditations-2008Singles.htm|title=ARIA certificates Singles 2008|publisher=Australian Recording Industry Association|accessdate=October 25, 2010}}</ref> In New Zealand, the song debuted on the chart at number 33.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://charts.nz/weekchart.asp?cat=s&year=2008&date=20080623|title=New Zealand Singles Top 40(23/06/2008)|date=June 23, 2008|publisher=[[New Zealand Singles Chart]]. [[Recording Industry Association of New Zealand]]|accessdate=October 31, 2010}}</ref> It reached number five a few weeks later.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://charts.nz/weekchart.asp?cat=s&year=2008&date=20080721|title=New Zealand Singles Top 40(21/07/2008)|date=July 21, 2008|publisher=New Zealand Singles Chart. Recording Industry Association of New Zealand|accessdate=October 31, 2010}}</ref> and was certified gold by the [[Recording Industry Association of New Zealand]] (RIANZ) for selling over 7,500 copies.<ref name=\"rianzcerti\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rianz.org.nz/rianz/chart.asp |title=Chart #1642: When I Grow Up Gold certification |date=September 10, 2009 |accessdate=October 25, 2010 |publisher=Recording Industry Association of New Zealand |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204021518/http://www.rianz.org.nz/rianz/chart.asp |archivedate=December 4, 2008 }}</ref> In the United Kingdom \"When I Grow Up\" debuted and peaked at number three on the [[UK Singles Chart]] with sales of 29,688.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.musicweek.com/story.asp?storycode=1035421 |title=Katy Perry gets physical at top of chart|publisher=[[Music Week]]. [[United Business Media]] |date=October 8, 2008 |accessdate=August 21, 2011|last=Jones |first=Alan}}</ref> On the ''Billboard'' [[European Hot 100 Singles]] the song peaked at number three, and also peaked at number nine in Germany.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/1303985/coldplay-perry-no-1-in-europe|title=Coldplay, Perry No. 1 In Europe|last=Sexton|first=Paul|date=October 11, 2008|work=Billboard|accessdate=October 21, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Critical response ==\n\"When I Grow Up\" received acclaim from music critics. Bill Lamb from About.com listed \"When I Grow Up\" among the top tracks on ''Doll Domination'', stating that the song \"bursts out of the blocks\", and that it was of no surprise that it \"landed in the pop top 10 with ease\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://top40.about.com/od/albums/fr/dolldomination.htm |title=Review of the Pussycat Dolls 2nd Album Doll Domination |accessdate=September 4, 2011|publisher=About.com. The New York Times Company|last=Lamb |first=Bill}}</ref> On a separate review, Lamb gave the song three out of five stars. He noted that the \"anonymous nature\" of the group's vocals and \"sexual lyrical tease\" is starting to wear thin, stating: \"This is more of the same, not a step forward\". Lamb, however, did compliment the song as being a \"catchy dance workout\", and stated that the song carries their \"usual sassiness\" and \"pounding dance beats\".<ref name=\"Lamb\"/> Nick Levine from [[Digital Spy]] echoed Lamb's comments, noting that the song is a \"bolshy, hyperactive pop stomper that works just as well in the aerobics class as it does on the dance-floor.\" He continued: \"If they keep releasing singles as infectious as this, they could last longer than we'd think.\"<ref name=\"Digispy\">{{cite web|last=Levine|first=Nick|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/singlesreviews/a109910/pussycat-dolls-when-i-grow-up.html|title=Music \u2013 Singles Review \u2013 Pussycat Dolls: 'When I Grow Up' |publisher=Digital Spy. Hachette Filipacchi M\u00e9dias|date=September 8, 2008|accessdate=November 5, 2010}}</ref> August Brown from ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called the song as the \"ideological centerpiece\" of ''Doll Domination''.<ref name=latimes>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2008/sep/16/entertainment/et-recordrack16|title=Smug Pussycat Dolls forget the fun|last=Brown|first=August|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=September 16, 2008|accessdate=November 5, 2010}}</ref>\n\nSal Cinquemani from [[Slant Magazine]] described the song as a \"catchy, full-throttle club track\" and commented that it is \"a perfectly concocted blend of camp and vamp for the famous burlesque troupe\".<ref name=\"slant\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/pussycat-dolls-doll-domination/1506|title=Pussycat Dolls: Doll Domination |magazine=[[Slant Magazine]]|last=Cinquemani|first=Sal|date=September 22, 2008|accessdate=November 1, 2010}}</ref> Steve Perkins from [[BBC Music]] awarded the song four out of five stars writing: \"It's good to see that the dynamics of the group remain fundamentally unchanged\" and that the song was a strong comeback.<ref name=\"Perkins\"/> He also noted that: \"The whole song seems to be centred around the desire to be famous when you grow up, which while not my favourite of all messages to give out to The Kids\". He ended his review writing \"but in all fairness: who cares? It's hella catchy, and really, who's the bigger fool here \u2013 the Pussycat Dolls lyricist who wrote some vaguely nonsensical lyrics, or the reviewer who expected anything different?\"<ref name=\"Perkins\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/chartblog/2008/09/pussycat_dolls_when_i_grow_up.shtml|title=Pussycat Dolls \u2013 'When I Grow Up' (Single Review) |publisher=[[BBC Music]]. [[BBC]] |last=Perkins |first=Steve |date=September 6, 2008 |accessdate=November 5, 2010}}</ref> Dan Cairns from ''[[The Times]]'' said that \"if every song here were as batty and brilliant as this, ''Doll Domination'' would be one of the great pop records of 2008.\"<ref name=cairns>{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/music/cd_reviews/article4775168.ece|title=Pussycat Dolls: Doll Domination CD reviews|last=Cairns|first=Dan|work=[[The Times]] |location=UK|date=September 13, 2008|accessdate=October 5, 2010}}</ref> However, Nic Oliver from [[MusicOMH]], in a review of ''Doll Domination'', did not favor the song, saying that the song would embarrass [[Paris Hilton]], but \"sets the template for the rest of the album.\"<ref name=\"musicomh\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.musicomh.com/albums/pussycat-dolls-2_0908.htm |title=Pussycat Dolls \u2013 Doll Domination &#124; album reviews |accessdate=June 25, 2010 |magazine=[[MusicOMH]] |last=Oliver |first=Nick |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100113132754/http://www.musicomh.com/albums/pussycat-dolls-2_0908.htm |archivedate=January 13, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n===Parodies and cover versions===\nThe song has been parodied on the video sharing website [[YouTube]] including a spoof called \"I Wanna Be a Pussycat Mom\" posted by The Momma Mary Show on September 9, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last=Burt-Godwin|first=Mary|title=when i grow up i wanna be a pussycat mom|url=http://www.mamamaryshow.com/2013/05/when-i-grow-up-i-wanna-be-a-pussycat-mom/|publisher=The Momma Mary Show|accessdate=April 15, 2014}}</ref> On June 3, 2008 the song was parodied by YouTube superstar [[Britney Houston]] as she recreated herself as part of the \"Britneycat Dolls\" and commented, \"When I do these things, I [usually] try to give a twist to the choreography. But [the Pussycat Dolls have] a signature move, and I just had to put it in there intact.\" It was posted on [[MTV]].com.<ref name = jimc1>{{cite news | last = Cantielo | first = Jim | title = Britney Houston Recruits 'Britney Cat Dolls' For Pussycat Dolls Parody | date = 2008-07-03 | url = http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1590362/20080702/the_pussycat_dolls.jhtml | accessdate = 2008-09-14}}</ref> \"When I Grow Up\" was later performed by [[Simone Battle]] while auditioning for ''[[The X Factor]]'' in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hilton|first=Perez|title=Our SECOND Favorite Audition From Last Night's X Factor!|url=http://perezhilton.com/2011-09-22-x-factor-audition-simone-battle#.U02-S-ZdV9k|accessdate=April 15, 2014|date=2011-09-22}}</ref> It has also been covered by [[Mayday Parade]] on the compilation album ''[[Punk Goes Pop 2]]'' in 2009,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/punk-goes-pop-vol.-2/id306304437|title=Punk Goes Pop, Vol. 2 by Various Artists|date=1 January 2009|publisher=}}</ref>  and [[The Glee Project]] in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://perezhilton.com/tv/The_Glee_Project_2_When_I_Grow_Up/?id=1d486e3700bdd#.U02xbeZdV9k|title=PerezTV Archives - Perez Hilton|website=Perez Hilton}}</ref>\n\n===Use in media===\nThe song was featured in the 2008 comedy film ''[[The House Bunny]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=The House Bunny (2008) - Soundtracks|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0852713/soundtrack|website=IMDb|accessdate=July 29, 2014}}</ref> the 2010 video game ''[[Just Dance 2]]''<ref>{{cite web|title=Just Dance 2 Tracks|url=http://just-dance-thegame.ubi.com/jd-portal/en-AU/just-dance-games/just-dance-2/index.aspx|website=Just Dance|publisher=UbiSoft|accessdate=July 29, 2014}}</ref>, and the episode \"Draggle Rock\", from the [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 5)|fifth season]] of ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=\"RuPaul's Drag Race\" Draggle Rock (TV Episode 2013) - Soundtrack|url=https://m.imdb.com/title/tt2662664/soundtrack?ref_=m_tt_trv_snd|website=IMDb|accessdate=March 7, 2020}}</ref> The song and its video were also featured briefly on the pilot for the Nickelodeon series ''[[Big Time Rush]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=\"Big Time Rush\" Big Time Audition (TV Episode 2009) - Soundtracks|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1589525/soundtrack?ref_=tt_ql_trv_7|website=IMDb|accessdate=July 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Music video ==\n[[File:PCD - When I Grow Up.png|thumb|right|260px|The Pussycat Dolls stuck in the middle of a traffic jam]]\n\nThe song's music video was shot on [[Hollywood Boulevard]] in Los Angeles, with director [[Joseph Khan]].{{cn|date=January 2020}} American recording artist [[Britney Spears]] filmed a cameo appearance for the video on June 4 at the [[Warner Bros.]] lot in Los Angeles.<ref name=\"britneycameo\">{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1588821/britney-spears-cameo-pussycat-dolls-video-report.jhtml|title=Britney Spears Looks 'Hot And Blonde' In Pussycat Dolls' 'When I Grow Up' Video: Report|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|publisher=MTV News. MTV Networks|date=June 5, 2008|accessdate=August 22, 2011}}</ref> An on set \"insider\" said that Spears' scene was short, only consisting of her driving in a passing car and waving to the other girls.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.x17online.com/news/2008/06/britney_spears_to_make_appeara.php |title=X17 News \u2013 Britney Spears to Make Appearance in Pussycat Dolls Music Video |publisher=X17online.com |date=June 5, 2008 |accessdate=September 25, 2011}}</ref> On June 12, 2008 it was announced by MTV News that the cameo had been cut from the final video.<ref name=\"britneyaxed\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1589190/britney-spears-cameo-axed-from-pussycat-dolls-video.jhtml|title=Britney Spears Cameo Axed From Pussycat Dolls Video|last=Kaufman|first=Gil|publisher=MTV News. MTV Networks|date=June 12, 2008|accessdate=June 29, 2010}}</ref> Scherzinger was asked why Spears got cut from the video.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2008/06/12/first-look-pussycat-dolls-when-i-grow-up/ |title=First Look: Pussycat Dolls \u2013 'When I Grow Up'|work=Rap-Up|publisher=Devine Lazerine |accessdate=December 30, 2011}}</ref> She said: \"I honestly am not so sure. You shoot a lot of things when you do a video. Some things stay in but other things don't make the cut and Britney just didn't make it. I've seen a little clip of her performance and she looked adorable so I really wish she was in it! Hopefully we'll work together in the future.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/interviews/a127709/pussycat-dolls.html|title=Music \u2013 Interview \u2013 Pussycat Dolls|last=Levine|first=Nick|date=September 1, 2008|publisher=Digital Spy. Hachette Filipacchi M\u00e9dias|accessdate=June 28, 2010}}</ref> A short clip of the music video was released online on June 12, 2008;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.interscope.com/artist/news/default.aspx?&aid=455&utmcampaign=interscope(fiona)&utmsource=myspace.com&utmmedium=myspaceblog&in=153|title=Pussycat Dolls : News : PCD's \"When I Grow Up\" Video Premiere 6/13!|work=Interscope Records|date=July 2, 2008|accessdate=August 21, 2011}}</ref> a day before the video's premiere on June 13, 2008 on [[FNMTV]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2008/06/13/video-pussycat-dolls-when-i-grow-up/ |title=Video: Pussycat Dolls \u2013 'When I Grow Up' |work=Rap-Up|publisher=Devine Lazerine |date=June 13, 2008 |accessdate=December 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn the video the Pussycat Dolls are shown sitting in a car in the middle of a traffic jam, where Scherzinger flashes a ring that says \"famous\". They sing the introduction of the song in the car before jumping out. When the chorus kicks in, the women leave the car and stand on the roofs of the other cars and start dancing a routine. Then they walk down a street of Hollywood stars with bubbles floating all around them. As they walk down the street, they also stop to sing on a bench. As the second chorus starts, the Dolls climb scaffolding and begin to dance. During Scherzinger's solo, she stands in a small area with the Pussycat Dolls logo to the left and a mirror to the right, with lights flashing. The Dolls then dance in the breakdown section with the logo behind them and the camera zooms out to reveal filming equipment and playback screens.\n\nNick Levine from Digital Spy, wrote that: \"The Pussycat Dolls have a novel way of amusing themselves during traffic jams\" and described the dance breakdown as \"entertaining\" and \"nostalgic\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Levine|first=Nick|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/thesound/a100752/watch-the-new-pussycat-dolls-video.html|title=Watch the new Pussycat Dolls video|work=Digital Spy|publisher=Hachette Filipacchi M\u00e9dias|date=June 16, 2008|accessdate=October 24, 2010}}</ref> In Australia, the video was criticized for the video being too raunchy.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/music/dolls-pop-up-charts/2008/06/30/1214677894245.html|title=Pussycat Dolls pop up charts|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|date=June 30, 2008|accessdate=October 24, 2010}}</ref> On August 17, 2008, it was announced that the video was nominated for [[MTV Video Music Award for Video of the Year|Video of the Year]], [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Dance Video|Best Dance Video]], [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Art Direction|Best Art Direction]], [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]], and [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Choreography|Best Choreography]] at the [[2008 MTV Video Music Awards]], having the most VMA nominations of that year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2008/09/04/vma-throwdown-thursday-pussycat-dolls-win-unofficial-vma-for-most-nominated-act-of-2008 |title=VMA Throwdown Thursday: Pussycat Dolls Win Unofficial VMA For Most-Nominated Act Of 2008 |first=Tamar |last=Anitay |publisher=MTV Buzzworthy. MTV Networks|date=September 4, 2008 |accessdate=August 21, 2011}}</ref> The ceremony was held on September 7, 2008, and the video won the award for the Best Dancing.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/ontv/vma/2008/|title=MTV Video Music Awards \u2013 2008 Winners|publisher=MTV. MTV Networks|accessdate=June 29, 2010}}</ref> The music video was the fifteenth-most streamed video on [[MTV.com]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1601234/weve-had-our-here-your-top-songs-2008.jhtml |title=We've Had Our Say, Here Are Your Top Songs Of 2008: Britney Spears, Lil Wayne And More! |first=James |last=Montgomery |publisher=MTV News, MTV Networks |date=August 15, 2008 |accessdate=August 21, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Live performances ==\n\"When I Grow Up\" was debuted live on American talk show ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'' on May 20, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|last=Castillo|first=Valerie Anne del|url=http://www.buddytv.com/articles/pussycat-dolls-present-the-search-for-the-next-doll/pussycat-dolls-present-their-n-19849.aspx|title='Pussycat Dolls Present' Their New Hit on Jimmy Kimmel, Gear Up for the Release of New CD |publisher=[[BuddyTV]]|date=May 25, 2008|accessdate=November 6, 2010}}</ref> On May 27, 2008 MTV News reported that the Pussycat Dolls were among many set to perform at the [[2008 MTV Movie Awards]] on June 1, 2008.<ref>{{cite news|last=Adler|first=Shawn|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1587434/coldplay-pussycat-dolls-set-perform-at-mtv-movie-awards.jhtml|title=Coldplay, Pussycat Dolls Set to Perform at MTV Movie Awards|publisher=MTV News. MTV Networks|date=May 27, 2008|accessdate=November 2, 2010}}</ref> Scherzinger talked about the performance saying: \"This is a big deal for us. We just want to kill it. It's all about the Dolls right now, and we're coming strong.\"<ref name=\"mtvnews\"/> The girls performed wearing spandex-and-leather getups,<ref name=\"mtvawards\"/> while a backdrop was displayed in the background with images of flashbulbs, tabloid headlines and diamonds.<ref>{{cite news |last=Montgomery |first=James |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1588438/behind-scenes-with-coldplay-pcd-at-movie-awards-rehearsal.jhtml |title=Behind The Scenes With Coldplay, PCD At Movie Awards Rehearsal \u2013 Show Story |publisher=MTV News. MTV Networks |date=May 31, 2008 |accessdate=September 5, 2011}}</ref> They were joined by ''[[America's Best Dance Crew]]'' winners the [[Jabbawockeez]] who descended from the ceiling wearing matching red T-shirts with stark-white masks covering their faces, and baseball caps perched at 45-degree angles atop their heads.<ref name=\"mtvawards\">{{cite news |last=Montgomery |first=James |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1588468/robert-downey-jr-king-backstage-at-mtv-movie-awards.jhtml |title=Robert Downey Jr. Is King, Tom Cruise Cheers On Pussycat Dolls: Backstage At The MTV Movie Awards |publisher=MTV News. MTV Networks |date=June 1, 2008 |accessdate=September 5, 2011}}</ref> Of the performance, Geoff Boucher from the ''Los Angeles Times'' commented: \"the Pussycat Dolls' set climaxed with a powerful pyro display that left celebs in the first few rows feeling a bit roasted\".<ref name=latimes2>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-mtv2-2008jun02,0,4775906.story|title=MTV Movie Awards impervious to studio fire|last=Boucher|first=Geoff|publisher=Tribune Company|work=The Los Angeles Times|date=June 2, 2008|accessdate=December 27, 2010}}</ref> MTV Buzzworthy described the performance as \"sexy\" and \"sultry\".<ref>{{cite news |author=Pop Cultured |url=http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2008/06/02/watch-or-rewatch-coldplay-and-pussycat-dolls-perform-at-the-mtv-movie-awards/ |title=Watch (Or Rewatch) Coldplay and Pussycat Dolls Perform at the MTV Movie Awards |publisher=MTV Buzzworthy. MTV Networks |date=June 2, 2008 |accessdate=September 5, 2011}}</ref> However, Tod Martens, in another review for the ''Los Angeles Times'', criticized their performance. He commented: \"[They appeared] onstage looking like they had escaped a taping for a sexed-up Jazzercise video.\"<ref name=latimes2/> He also wrote that Scherzinger never commanded the song except on \"the cut's final seconds when she turned her vocals up to a growl\" and noted JabbaWockeez's appearance as \"annoy[ing]\".<ref name=latimes3>{{cite news|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080612125011/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/extendedplay/2008/06/mtv-movie-award.html|archivedate=June 12, 2008|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/extendedplay/2008/06/mtv-movie-award.html |title=MTV Movie Awards: Coldplay and the Pussycat Dolls were ready to sell |last=Martens |first=Tod |publisher=Tribune Company |work=The Los Angeles Times |date=June 1, 2008 |accessdate=September 5, 2011}}</ref>\n\n\"When I Grow Up\" was also performed at ''[[So You Think You Can Dance (U.S. TV series)|So You Think You Can Dance]]'' on June 13, 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2008/06/13/video-pussycat-dolls-perform-on-so-you-think-you-can-dance/ |title=Video: Pussycat Dolls Perform on So You Think You Can Dance |date=June 13, 2008 |publisher=Rap-Up. Devine Lazerine |accessdate=September 5, 2011}}</ref> On August 2, 2008 the Dolls performed the song and presented at the [[MTV Asia Awards 2008]] in [[Kuala Lumpur]], Malaysia, along with \"[[Buttons (The Pussycat Dolls song)|Buttons]]\" (2005).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2008/08/03/pussycat-dolls-at-mtv-asia-awards-2008/ |title=Pussycat Dolls at MTV Asia Awards 2008 |date=August 3, 2008 |publisher=Rap-Up. Devine Lazerine |accessdate=September 5, 2011}}</ref> The group then performed the song at the Walmart Soundcheck, along with \"[[I Hate This Part]]\", \"Takin' Over the World\", \"Buttons\" and \"Don't Cha\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soundcheck.walmart.com/pussycat-dolls|title=Walmart Soundcheck 2008 \u2013 Watch Pussycat Dolls Interviews, Live Performances, Music Videos|work=[[Wal-Mart]]|accessdate=November 2, 2010}}</ref> On November 21, they performed a medley of \"I Hate This Part\" and \"When I Grow Up\" at the [[2008 American Music Awards]]. The performance included stripper poles, and the girls donned all-rubber outfits.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2008-11-24/entertainment/17910371_1_fishnet-rubber-two-awards |title=Rihanna, Christina Aguilera, Beyonce, more rack up the sex appeal at AMAs |last=Miller |first=Korin |date=October 24, 2008 |accessdate=September 5, 2011 |work=[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]] |publisher=[[Mortimer Zuckerman]]}}</ref> The Pussycat Dolls also performed \"When I Grow Up\" at the [[Doll Domination Tour]] (2009). Maureen Ellis of the ''[[Evening Times]]'' said that the \"high-energy encore of 'Don't Cha' and 'When I Grow Up' ensured the Dolls reigned supreme.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/review-purr-fect-dolls-conquer-glasgow-1.966765 |title=Review: Purr-fect Dolls conquer Glasgow |last=Maureen |first=Ellis |publisher=[[Evening Times]] (Herald & Times Group) |date=January 20, 2009 |accessdate=September 5, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn November 26, 2019, they performed \"When I Grow Up\" in a medley on [[The X Factor: Celebrity]] with \"[[Buttons (The Pussycat Dolls song)|Buttons]]\", \"[[Don't Cha]]\" & \"[[React (The Pussycat Dolls song)|React]]\" to promote their [[Unfinished Business (tour)|2020 reunion tour]]. \n\nOn February 22, 2020, they performed \"When I Grow Up\" in their performance at [[G-A-Y]].\n\n== Formats and track listings ==\n{{col begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n*'''Digital download'''<ref 